Date: Fri 5 Feb 2010
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@vetmed.lsu.edu> [edited]


Re: Afghan heroin in Russia
---------------------------
In a previous posting (see archive no. 20100203.0368) we reported that
the heroin in the UK comes from Afghanistan via the Balkans where it
is processed and repackaged, before being shipped by road to a Channel
port. The identical genomic identity of the German case in Aachen to
the Scottish cases indicates that in this case they were using the
port of Antwerp.

Russia is severely afflicted with heroin, which the government hints
follows from the Western intervention in Afghanistan. Unfortunately
the Russian drug policy is counterproductive. Any addict who seeks
medical help for his or her addiction is immediately put on the state
"narcological register". This information is available to police, who
can have the drug user arrested and put in prison, and causes huge
problems for people if they kick their habit and want to reintegrate
into society.

But to date there are no reports of heroin related human anthrax in
Russia, which would reinforce the hypothesis that the anthrax
contamination problem is in the Balkans. The usual contamination
problems associated with heroin, however, are occurring.

There are a number of reports worth reading on the Russian heroin problem:
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7935527.stm>,
<http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-finally-admits-to-its-
hidden-heroin-epidemic-1642103.html>,
<http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/03/11/russia-finally-admits-to_n_173924.html>,
<http://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/25/world/fg-russia-heroin25>,
<http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Heroin-Russia-Blames-Coalition-Over-Afghanistan-Drug-Supply-Increase/Article/200912315500702>,
and
<http://www.tehrantimes.com/Index_view.asp?code=212477>.

